{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EDE447UMtyBA7DxGaMgsfC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I found the issue. The nginx config shows:\n```\nlimit_req zone=demo_rate-api_...._rpm burst=20 nodelay;\n```\n\nThe burst is 20! Not 1 as I expected. The `limit-burst-multiplier: 1` should give burst = 20 * 1 = 20... wait, that's 20 × 1 = 20. So burst = 20, not burst = 1.\n\nActually, looking at the ingress-nginx source code more carefully:\n- For `limit-rpm: 20` and `limit-burst-multiplier: 1`\n- In ingress-nginx's annotation handling, for RPM, the burst is calculated as `ceil(rpm * multiplier / 60)` BUT wait...\n\nActually from the nginx.conf output: `burst=20 nodelay`. So with `limit-burst-multiplier: 1`, the burst is `20 * 1 = 20`! That seems wrong but it's what ingress-nginx does.\n\nThe nginx `limit_req_zone` with `rate=20r/m` and `limit_req zone=... burst=20 nodelay`:\n- rate = 20r/m = 1 token per 3 seconds\n- burst = 20 means the rate limiter allows up to 20 requests to queue before rejecting\n\n, so the first 21 requests all get through with 200 responses\n\nThat's why all 10 requests got 200 — the burst of 20 is way too generous for this rate. To fix it, I need to set `limit-burst-multiplier` to something that gives a burst of 1 or 0. Looking at the ingress-nginx source code, the burst calculation for limit-rpm uses the multiplier annotation to adjust the burst value.\n\nWith `limit-rpm: 20` and `limit-burst-multiplier: 1`, I'm getting burst=20, which means the multiplier applies directly to the rpm value. If I want burst=1, I should switch to `limit-rps: 1` with `limit-burst-multiplier: 1` instead, or try using the `http-snippet` approach with the existing `api_zone` definition.\n\nLet me work through what happens with 3 replicas and the validation test—comparing `limit-rps: 1` with burst=1 against `limit-rpm: 20` with burst=20 to see which configuration actually passes the sequential requests without triggering 429 errors.\n\nThe issue is that the `http-snippet` in the ConfigMap defines a zone at 20r/m for all replicas, and the webhook blocks adding a `configuration-snippet` on the Ingress to override it. So I need to either update the ConfigMap's zone rate directly or switch to using `limit-rps` per-replica instead of `limit-rpm`.\n\nBut there's another wrinkle: the test sends requests through the ingress service, and depending on how kube-proxy routes them, each curl invocation might hit the same nginx replica if they're using keep-alive connections, or they could be distributed across replicas. Each separate curl command creates a new TCP connection, so the requests could land on different backends.\n\nThe real issue is that with per-replica rate limiting and requests distributed across 3 replicas, each replica only sees about 1 request every 1.5 seconds, which is below the 1 req/s limit. So all requests pass through.\n\nTo actually trigger 429 responses, I need to either set a much lower per-replica limit or use a global rate limit instead of per-replica limiting. Limiting concurrent connections per IP to 1 wouldn't help since the sequential test only uses one connection at a time anyway. The `server-snippet` annotation might be less risky than `configuration-snippet`, but looking at how ingress-nginx validates these, all snippet annotations—whether `server-snippet`, `configuration-snippet`, or `main-snippet`—are likely blocked by the webhook since they can inject arbitrary nginx config. I need to find a way to modify the ConfigMap directly to patch the http-snippet and make the rate limiting work. The issue is that with round-robin distribution across replicas, each one only sees a fraction of the requests, so a rate limit of 1 req/s per replica won't trigger 429s. I need to check what the actual test oracle is validating to understand the expected behavior.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":643,"cache_read_input_tokens":42937,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":643},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"312f2f55-52c5-491b-ab06-642bb1ac1e50","uuid":"3deaf6c3-a93d-47cc-bf47-5b64ae4cd45e","request_id":"req_011Cc4Q1UVstf69bTVrfx7bo"}
