et rejected because the decay isn't fast enough to bring the counter below the threshold before the next request arrives.\n\nWith a single replica receiving all 10 requests, only the first one passes while the remaining 9 get rejected—meeting the requirements. Even if requests distribute across 3 replicas, each replica's first request passes while later ones are rejected, still satisfying the constraint of at least 4 rejections and at least 1 success.\n\nNow I need to implement this by updating the ConfigMap's http-snippet to change the `api_zone` rate from 20r/m down to 1r/m, since zone definitions must live at the http context level rather than in location-level configuration snippets.\n\nLooking back at the test results, I'm seeing an interesting pattern in the response codes—positions 3 and 9 returned 429s while the rest got 200s. Let me trace through how these requests might have distributed across the three replicas to understand why certain positions hit the rate limit.\n\nIf requests are being distributed round-robin, I'd expect Replica 1 to receive requests at t=0 and t=1.5 seconds. With a rate limit of 20 requests per minute (about 0.33 requests per second), the token bucket calculation shows that by t=1.5, the counter should have dropped below the threshold, which would trigger a 429. But position 4 got a 200 instead, so either the load balancing isn't actually round-robin and requests are clustering on fresher replicas, or the rate limit configuration is only being applied to one of the three `/api` location blocks in the nginx config rather than all of them.\n\nActually, I'm realizing all three location blocks share the same `api_zone` and use the same rate limit state keyed by the client IP, so they should all be enforcing the same limit within a single replica. The real issue is probably how requests are being distributed across replicas. Let me just lower the rate limit to 1 request per minute in the ConfigMap snippet—that way even if requests hit di